-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - March 26
-- 
-- Tue Mar 25, 2014 10:06PM EDT
-- None



March 26 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  CANDY CRUSH DEVELOPER'S IPO RAISES $500 MLN DESPITE INVESTOR FEARS (http://link.reuters.com/wur87v)  UK GOVERNMENT TO SELL A FIFTH OF LLOYDS STAKE (http://link.reuters.com/zur87v)  FACEBOOK BETS $2 BLN ON VIRTUAL REALITY (http://link.reuters.com/vur87v)  BANKS PAY OUT $100 BLN IN US FINES (http://link.reuters.com/cyr87v)  SANTANDER UK FACES 12.5 MLN STG FINE OVER POOR ADVICE (http://link.reuters.com/xur87v)  Overview  Mobile game maker King Digital Entertainment <KING.N> raised $500 million from its stock market float late on Tuesday, valuing the company's equity at $8 billion on a fully diluted basis and making it one of the most valuable.  Britain's government announced plans to sell more than 4 billion pounds worth of its shares in Lloyds Banking Group <LLOY.L>, moving a step closer to returning the lender to the private sector before next year's election.  Facebook <FB.O> said it would buy Oculus VR, a maker of virtual-reality glasses for gaming, placing a $2 billion bet that virtual reality headsets will be the next big social platform after computers and smartphones.  Banks have shelled out $100 billion in U.S. legal settlements since the financial crisis, according to Financial Times research, reflecting a substantial shift in political attitudes towards the financial sector.